    "body": "### Problem\n\nWhen I want to open a remote file using the scp protocol by netrw, I can see that it uses for destination path  `/C/Users/...`. The command fails by printing \"No such file or directory\". When reading the doc,s I found the variable for netrw called  `g:netrw_cygwin` that maybe uses the Unix-like path style. Even if I set the variable to 0, it stills try use for destination `/C/Users/...`\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n(on Windows) : `nvim scp://user@hostname/file/to/edit`\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nInstead of setting the destination path `/C/Users`, getting something more like that `C:\\Users\\...`\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\n0.10.0\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nsame\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nWindows 10\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nPowershell\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\n?\n\n### Installation\n\nBinary from realease",
